title: For Sale:  Antique ( 1888 -1897) Harrington 32 revolver
postcontent:
Harrington & Richardson  antique “The American Double Action “  (large solid frame center fire revolver) Manufactured 1883–1941.  This one is the third variation made from 1888 to 1897 so it is from 127 years old to 118 years old.  I have included information on this antique from the internet below. 
Firearm has the following defect or I do not know how to operate it

When you pull the trigger the hammer comes back and strikes firmly.  The cylinder does not rotate nor the the trigger rebound automatically for the next shot. The trigger must be pushed forward so it needs repair. This apparently is a black powder pistol for a collection and must not be fired with modern high pressure ammo just black powder cartridges designed for 100 year old firearms  


It appears to be Calibers: .32,  

Info from the Internet 

.32, .38, or .44 cal., 5 (.38 or .44) or 6 (.32 cal.) shot, 2 1/2, 4 1/2, or 6 in. barrel, nickel (standard) or blue (rare) finish, pull pin cylinder release, marked on top strap "THE AMERICAN DOUBLE ACTION", first variation has round barrel and nickel trigger guard with rear retaining pin offset to rear slightly (1884 only), second variation has round barrel and nickel trigger guard (1884-1887), third variation has octagon barrel and nickel trigger guard (1888-1897), fourth variation has octagon barrel, blue trigger guard and company name and address on left side of barrel (1898-1904). Mfg. 1884-1904. 




H&R made three variations of this model from 1884 to 1904. Mine is a second variation, made between 1887 and 1897. The differences were mostly cosmetic. Most of these revolvers were made with a nickel finish, something quite popular at the time, and sold for around a dollar or two.

This revolver is chambered in .32 Smith and Wesson and is designed for black powder cartridges. The second model American, made from 1905 to 1942 shot smokeless powder.



This was a pretty basic gun. It could hold six rounds (although with the hammer-mounted firing pin, five is the rule) in the cylinder. There is a loading gate on the right side of the revolver. The cylinder is removable by pulling the pin under the barrel.

This little (and it is little - the barrel is 2.5" long) critter works just fine and can squirt an 85 grain round nose lead bullet downrange at the sedate pace of about 600fps. Recoil is a little more than that of a similarly sized .22. The black powder does produce satisfactory smoke and fire, though, so it makes up with drama for the lack of oomph.



The American was chambered in .32S&W, .32H&R, .38S&W and .44 Webley. H&R stopped making revolvers during World War II and contracted to build weapons for the military. After the war, they continued with a different line of guns and The American faded into glory.

H&R went out of business in 1986, but was resurrected in 1991 as a subsidiary of Marlin.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Beretta designed Chiappa M9 .22LR Plinker
location: King of Prussia, Southeastern, PA, Pennsylvania
postcontent:
It is made similar to the Beretta architecture and both the original Beretta and this Chiappa exhibit the same profile, controls, and double-action/single-action trigger, but uses a frame cast from a zinc alloy the company refers to as Chiappalloy. Both the process and material are sufficient for the lower pressures of the .22 Long Rifle cartridge. The gun’s 37-ounce weight is surprising, given its chambering. It’s not until wallets are weighed that the M9-22 regains its charm.

I have had a lot of fun with this wonderful pistol. I have put 939 rounds through it since I bought it back 2013.

This Chiappa’s magazine release, slide release lever, decocker/manual safety, hammer, and take down lever all function like its center-fire brethren, except the decocker/manual safety and the sights are made of plastic rather than metal. Its 10-round magazine is made from plastic, save the spring, and weighs 1.5 ounces. I appreciate that it falls free of the magazine well when released.

The only problem I have had with this gun is that the mag release button got damaged and Chiappa fixed it for free and it works just as it did the day I bought it.

The decocker/manual safety system is a proven one. Safely drop the hammer by rolling the ambidextrous decocking lever down. This movement disconnects and shields the firing pin by rolling it up and out of the path of the hammer. With the lever and therefore the hammer in the down position—the safe position—the trigger can still be pulled in double-action mode, thereby cocking and dropping the hammer, without the possibility of firing. If the gun is dropped accidentally, the firing pin block prevents it from reaching the primer unless the trigger is pulled. To fire, rotate the decocking/manual safety up, then either pull the trigger in double-action mode, or manually cock the hammer to fire the first round in single-action mode. Despite the decocker/safety being made of plastic, it functions fine.

The M9-.22’s trigger is a replica of the original and for that reason it is a great source of love or loathe to individual shooters. It uses a reliable system that creates cocking leverage by pulling an external, sliding trigger bar that engages the hammer when the slide is installed. Trigger pressure cocks the hammer before pushing the sear disconnect forward to release it. The double-action trigger pull measured slightly more than 12 pounds—so stout some petite shooters like my wife can't pull it without losing the line of sight.

postcontent: Russian SKS-45 for sale...This gun is stamped Russian SKS-45 on the receiver (most others just say Russian SKS)..It has no production year or markings on the receiver cover, my research shows the 55 and 56 production years had no year or markings on the cover but they also have a lightening hole on either side of the lug (mine does not),,,The 55-56 production also have a small Tula star stamped in the receiver (mine does not)..It appears my rifle is a 50 or 51 due to comparing photos of various parts...The rifle also has a low 3 digit serial number and a triangle with a number 1 inside it just to the left and below the serial number on the receiver, which is a East German proof mark that makes this a DDR Simonovs rifle (this also contributes to it not being marked on the receiver cover)..The gun also has a horizontal serial number stamped in the stock and forearm unlike the typical vertical stamping of the serial number,,research shows this an uncommon type of refurb and there aren't many like it...My rifle has the retracting spring for the firing pin  (they did away with this in 52) and it has all the other features of the 50 and 51. Gun also has the original cleaning kit in the butt stock but is missing the actual cleaning rod, other than that it is a complete and matching numbers gun. Once again this is the Russian SKS-45 with the East German mark (a number 1 inside a triangle just to the left and slightly below the serial number on the receiver). I am legally allowed to possess a Handgun, I can show you my CCP and Mil ID so you know I'm not a felon. I do not own a shop, I do this as a hobby and to help people with cost. I will however do the same if not better job then you will get at a gunshop for a fraction of the price, you can pay over $100 for a polish job at gunshops! I enjoy gunwork and I do this as a hobby, I have been for many years and I am very familiar with Glocks and many others, just shoot me a message with what gun you have. Turnaround is 48hrs, however in most cases it is ready for pickup next day, I say 48hrs for a 1 day buffer in case I have something going on with work. Cant beat that! Also I can install what ever custom parts you have purchased on your own. There will be a "Pre" and "Post" work form to fill out stating what services will be provided and that your giving and taking back possession. A copy will be made for you to keep.
 -------------------------------------------------
 Why Polish Internals?:
 Polishing is like waxing a floor. Less friction equals smoother surface, which in our case equals a physically smoother operating gun and a smoother feel to the user. It will remove most/all of the grittiness in your trigger as well as making a smoother pull and reset. Glocks come stock with a 5lb trigger pull which in reality is closer to 6lb, sometimes slightly more, due to all the friction from factory coated parts. Polishing will bring it to where it should be with stock parts which is roughly 4.5lbs-5lbs, thus making the trigger pull feel lighter then your used to. I also offer two parts to further reduce trigger pull and enhance smoothness, that when coupled with the polish job will make your Glock operate as smooth as possible and make the trigger pull break like glass every time....Pull the trigger on one of my glocks before you commit and see for yourself!
 -------------------------------------------------
 What I offer:
 I will completely disassemble the gun(slide and frame), clean the entire gun(bore at your request), polish all friction prone internals, oil and reassemble. Can also polish Barrel Feed Ramp at your request with no additional Fee.
 Price $25

 I will Remove the Factory 5lb Connector and replace it with a POLISHED 3.5lb connector. This reduces the trigger pull to roughly 3lbs-3.5lbs.
 Price $15

 I will Remove the Factory 5lb Trigger Spring and Replace it with a 6lb Trigger Spring. Why heavier here? The Trigger Spring actually assists the Trigger in Pull/Reset, a Heavier one will make for a Smoother pull and Smoother Reset.
 Price $5

 I will refinish your scratched/worn barrel by slightly sanding, degreasing and applying an even coat of Black DuraCoat DuraBake which is a heat treated form of Duracoat making it hard as nails once its heated.
 $15

 For any custom parts you would like installed, please let me know and I will give you a quote. I can install parts you bought or I can order them for you at a discounted rate and save you some money.
 -------------------------------------------------
 Turnaround is 48hrs, however in most cases it is ready for pickup next day, I say 48hrs for a 1 day buffer in case I have something going on with work. Cant beat that! Also I can install what ever custom parts you have purchased on your own. There will be a "Pre" and "Post" work form to fill out stating what services will be provided and that your giving and taking back possession. A copy will be made for you to keep.

 Feel free to contact me to setup a time, thanks.
 Chris

title: For Sale/Trade:  20" AR-15, varmint/target setup - unfired
postcontent:
I have a 20" AR that I put together for shooting out to and beyond 400 yards. 

Gun is unfired, I never found the time to take it out to go shooting. Only reason I am considering selling it is because I finished getting it together in mid-September and here we are in late February and it still has yet to have a single round fired. 

The lower receiver is a Delaware Machinery, the LPK is CMMG. It has a Magpul ACS-L stock and an MOE grip with punisher skull engraved. Both are in OD Green. It currently has a POF trigger with KNS Anti-rotation pins installed. 

The upper is a complete Palmetto upper, 20" 1-8 twist hammer forged 410 stainless steel medium profile barrel. M4 barrel extension, rifle-length gas system with low profile gas block. 223 Wylde chamber, so it is great for shooting both 5.56 and 223 rem ammo. It has a YHM Phantom flash hider installed as well as a Midwest Industries SS Keymod 15" free float handguard. 
The BCG and CH are PSA, PSA logo is laser engraved on the bolt carrier

Has 45 degree offset flip up sights and a Mueller 4.5-14x40 scope. Has target turrets and adjustable objective. 

I am offering a few options. I would prefer to sell everything as a package, and the best deal will be had buying everything as a packaged deal.

I have a lot of money invested into this rifle. (none of these prices include shipping or tax)

Lower- $80
LPK - $60
Buffer kit and magpul stock - $100
Engraved grip - $25
POF trigger/anti rotation pins - $180
PSA complete upper - $550
PSA BCG + CH - $100
YHM Flash Hider $30
Flip up sights $50
Mueller Scope - $180

I have over $1350 into this. Not expecting to get all of that back, but for a complete and unfired gun please do not thing you can rake me over the coals either. 

I am willing to consider cash or trade (with cash going either way depending on what the trade is worth, my cash prices are not the trade value, trade value must be close to what I have invested in the gun). 

I would like to get $1150 for everything as listed. 

For $1000 I will let the gun go without the scope. 

For $900 I will let the gun go without the scope and with a mil-spec fire control group. 

For $650 I will sell just the complete upper with BCG, CH and back up sights.

My asking prices on each setup are firm. I have a lot more money into this than I am asking, and they represent the most I am willing to lose on this investment. If I cannot get that value out of this setup I will gladly let it sit in the safe until the time comes that I can get out and make use of this rifle.
